EXERCISE XLII

(rar-123) INDIRECT OBJECT WITH THE IMPERSONAL PASSIVE

It has previously been pointed out that intransitive verbs are of two types, namely l 1) those which are incapable of governing any case whatsoever, and (2) those which are construed with some case other than the accusative; and, further, it has been shown that all intransitive verbs are necessarily restricted, in the passive, toan impersonal use (ci. Exercise XXVI).

The passive oi intransitives oi the first type is already familiar (ag. pugnetur, pugnatum est, etc). On the next page is illustrated the corresponding passive oi certain

intransitives ol the other type.
